#welcome!
this tutorial explains how to create nodes in slidenotes.io

hit `escape` or the **x-button** ![](x-button.svg) to look up the code structure of the slide, explore the menus and play around with the content.
a click on the **play button** ![](playbutton.svg) brings you back to the preview.

---
## what are nodes? 
and why should I bother? 

some data can be best expressed by displaying them in a node diagram.

showing how elements are related to each other, it can be useful whenever we want to map out some sort of connection—may it be chronological, hierarchical or otherwise structured.

a quick example would be the flow of a process: 

+++node
start->end: process
+++

let's get started ➡︎

----
## node tags

+++layout:left
just like any other code element, the node tag can be selected from the **toolbar** ![](toolbar.svg).

if you want to write the code by hand, you have to start with ~+++node~ and end with ~+++~.
the lines inside the node tag are used to build the different nodes.

when writing them, you have to follow their very own syntax. 
but don't be scared!
it's very user friendly, intuitive and easy to remember.
you won't have a hard time learning it.

you'll see ➡︎
+++

---
## connections

+++layout:inline
first, let's build a connection. 
in order to have something to connect, we'll throw in two nodes by writing ~first node~ and ~second node~.

+++code
 +++node
 first node
 second node
 +++
+++

+++node
first node 
second node
+++
+++

+++layout:inline
now, let's bring these two together in one line and insert a connection by writing ~->~

+++code
 +++node
 first node -> second node
 +++
+++

+++node
first node -> second node
+++
+++

----
## messages

+++layout:left
just like that, we made our first node connection.
easy, right?
let's keep on building: 
how about adding a message to the connection?

to do so, we are typing in ~: a message~ right after the second node.
+++

+++layout:right

+++code
 +++node
 first node -> second node: a message
 +++
+++

+++node
first node -> second node: a message
+++

+++

----
## node names

+++layout:left

as you might have noticed, our nodes actually displayed the names we had given them. so let's try to customize:

+++code
 +++node
 sender -> receiver: a message
 +++
+++

+++node
sender -> receiver: a message
+++
+++

+++layout:right
once we found the perfect names,we can reuse them in different lines of the node tag, always referring to the same nodes:

+++code
 +++node
 sender -> receiver: a message
 receiver -> sender: a reply
 +++
+++

+++node
sender -> receiver: a message
receiver -> sender: a reply
+++
+++
---
## connector types

connections aren't all the same. so neither should connectors.

change their syntax to change their type.

+++node
1 -> 2
2 --> 3
+++
+++node
3 => 4
4 - 5
+++
+++node
5 -- 6
+++



+++layout:left

+++table
to build |like in |use
a normal arrow   |1 to 2 |->
a dashed arrow   |2 to 3 |-->
a broad arrow    |3 to 4 |=> 
a simple line    |4 to 5 |- 
a dashed red line|5 to 6 |--
+++
+++

+++layout:right

look this up whenever you need: 
the **node context menu** ![](node context menu.svg) will give you a list.
+++

## time to play


at this point you should hit `escape` and check out the code of the nodes on this slide. 
don't be afraid to mess around: copy, change, add, delete, create your own. 
when you're done hit the **play button** ![](playbutton.svg) to continue with the tutorial.


+++node
red parrot => green parrot: hi
green parrot => red parrot: hello
+++

+++node
stranded sailor -> ocean: bottled text
ocean --> stranger: bottled text
+++

+++node
owner -> tenant: flat
tenant -> roomie: room
+++


---
## declaring node names: 
aliases

+++layout:left

so far we built connections by naming nodes inside the tag: 

for simple nodes, this method is quick and handy. but what if we want to built more complex structures? writing the names over and over again can become a real hassle. 
lucky for you, there's a shortcut to it: *declaring the names just once, then keep on working with aliases.*
+++

+++layout:right
+++code
 +++node
 parrot -> human: hello
 human => parrot: hi
 +++
+++

+++node
a: parrot
b: human

a->b: hello
b=>a: hi
+++

+++code
 +++node
 a: parrot
 b: human

 a -> b: hello
 b => a: hi
 +++
+++
+++

---
## declaring node names: 
aliases

feel free to use your own aliases: just choose whatever works best for you.
*anything* will do, as long as you declare it in the node tag.
and that's *anywhere* in the node tag, really—no need to use the first lines.


+++code
 +++node
 start: camp
 start -> 1
 1 --> 2
 2 -> start
 1: temple
 2: village
 +++
+++

+++node
start: camp
start -> 1
1 --> 2
2 -> start
1: temple
2: village
+++

---
## node shapes

+++layout:left
you're becoming a real node tag pro. 
time for a shiny new tool! ![](slidenotes_yay.svg)
it's a shape feature helping you categorize by giving special shapes to special nodes:

+++node
[square]
(circle)
+++

+++node
<diamond>
{cloud}
+++
+++

+++layout:right
the syntax is easy—slidenotes style.
you want a square? use ~[]~ square brackets:

+++code
 +++node
 [square shaped node]
 +++
+++

+++table
syntax|node shape
[ ]| square
( )| circle
< >| diamond
{ }| cloud
+++
+++

---
## output options

+++layout:left

there's more you can change about the look of your nodes. 
the data output style for instance.
the nodes we used so far, all showed a **simple flow**:

+++node
simple - flow
+++

that's our default output option, but there are actually three more:
they're called **flow**, **tree** and **sequence** and you can look them all up in the **node context menu** ![](node context menu.svg)

let's go and check them out ➡︎
+++

---
## output options

to change the output of your data, you have to change the ~+++node~ tag header.
just add an ~:~ and declare the option:

+++code
 +++node: flow
 flowing - down
 +++
+++


+++node: flow
flowing - down
+++


---
##output options: 
tree

the ~+++node: tree~ output is a good way to display relations in organized systems.

+++layout:inline

+++node: tree
fox - rabbit
rabbit - carrot
+++
+++

in order to show hierarchy, ~: tree~ data gets read hierarchically.
so when the content of your node tag gets interpreted, the diagrams job is to follow your lead.

now your job is to lead it right ➡︎ 

---
##output options: 
tree

+++layout: inline
any node you write first in line will be shown on top. connecting yet another node results in a downwards flow.

+++node: tree
one - two
+++

+++code
 +++node: tree
 one - two
 +++
+++
+++

+++hidden
+++layout:inline
+++code
 +++node: tree
 one - two
 two - one
 +++
+++

+++node: tree
one - two
two - one
+++

once a connection is built you can add a reversing one.
+++
+++

+++hidden
+++layout:inline
whenever you add nodes that aren't yet connected, they appear on top again and right next to the first.

+++node: tree
one - two
two - one
three
+++

+++code
 +++node: tree
 one - two
 two - one
 three
 +++
+++
+++
+++

---
## output options: 
sequence

+++layout:inline
by using the output ~: sequence~ you can show many exchanges that happen in seperate sequences. 
like when bob and alice talk in this node example:

+++node:sequence
a: alice
b: bob
a -> b: you hear me?
b -> a: yes, great.
a -> b: yes, *what*?
b -> a: **great!**
a -- b
b --> a: hello?
b --> a: alice?
b --> a: great.
+++

+++code:none
  +++node:sequence
  a: alice
  b: bob
  a -> b: you hear me?
  b -> a: yes, great.
  a -> b: yes, *what*?
  b -> a: **great!**
  a -- b
  b --> a: hello?
 b --> a: alice?
 b --> a: great.
 +++
+++
+++

+++hidden
let's give this talk some context by writing additional notes ➡︎
+++

---
## notes

+++node:sequence
a: alice
b: bob
note over a: with bad reception
note left of a: calls
note right of b: picks up
a -> b: you hear me?
b -> a: yes, great.
note over a: confused
a -> b: yes, *what*?
note right of b: shouts
b -> a: **great!**
note left of a: hangs up
a -- b
note right of b: talks to void
b --> a: hello?
b --> a: alice?
b --> a: great.
note over b: annoyed
+++

---
## notes

notes are a way of altering node diagrams with extra information.

+++node
[node] - (node): connector
(node) - <node>: connector
note left of (node): note
note right of (node): note
note over (node): note
+++

they can be placed *beside* nodes or *on top* of them.

in the node tag code, they are written like this:

~note~ ~left of~ node name~:~ note text
~note~ ~right of~ node name~:~ note text
~note~ ~over~ node name~:~ note text

----
## notes

+++layout:left
+++node:sequence
(circle) -> {cloud}
note over (circle): over circle
(circle) -> {cloud}
note left of (circle): left of circle
note right of (circle): right of circle
(circle) -> {cloud}
note over {cloud}: over cloud
(circle) -> {cloud}
note left of {cloud}: left of cloud
note right of {cloud}: right of cloud
(circle) -> {cloud}
+++
+++

+++layout:right
+++code:none
 +++node:sequence
 (circle) -> {cloud}
 note over (circle): over circle
 (circle) -> {cloud}
 note left of (circle): left of circle
 note right of (circle): right of circle
 (circle) -> {cloud}
 note over {cloud}: over cloud
 (circle) -> {cloud}
 note left of {cloud}: left of cloud
 note right of {cloud}: right of cloud
 (circle) -> {cloud}
 +++
+++
+++
